title: From the Château de Versailles to the Elysée, the unshakable Catherine Pégard
subhed: Against all odds and well beyond her legal term, the former journalist who became adviser to President Nicolas Sarkozy held on as head of the Château de Versailles for 12 years. Forced out of her position in 2024, the skillful and tenacious Catherine Pégard quickly found a seat at the Elysée as culture adviser. Now, rumors suggest she could replace Rachida Dati, currently running for Paris City Hall, if she gives up her ministerial post.

subhed: The younger brother of Britain's King Charles was arrested earlier Thursday on suspicion of misconduct during his time as a trade envoy. New revelations appeared to show Andrew sent convicted US sex offender Jeffrey Epstein potentially confidential documents.

title: USA's Alysa Liu wins the gold in Olympic women's figure skating
subhed: The 20-year-old put the US women back on top of the Olympic women's podium in this event for the first time since Sarah Hughes took gold at the 2002 Salt Lake City Games.

title: In Dhaka, Sheikh Hasani's palace has been turned into a museum honoring victims of the July 2024 uprising
subhed: At the center of the vast property in front of the entrance, a monument has been erected in memory of all the victims of the 'Iron Lady's' regime. The museum is set to open to the public in the coming weeks.

title: Anthropic, the AI start-up that dares to defy Donald Trump
subhed: Dario Amodei, the CEO of the artificial intelligence company, acknowledged disagreements with the White House over the regulation and military use of his technology. This is a rare stance in the US, where the tech industry has generally pledged allegiance to the president.
